21
00:07:30,246 --> 00:07:36,896
[SPEAKER_15]: Action and discussion items 26074 submitted by Office of Planning, Development and Sustainability, Community Development Block Grant Action Plan for Fiscal 27.

22
00:07:38,660 --> 00:07:44,004
[SPEAKER_15]: The purpose of this meeting is to discuss the city's community development block grant annual action plan for community development and planning.

23
00:07:44,104 --> 00:07:50,349
[SPEAKER_15]: The action plan contains the proposed use of community development block grant funds for the program year, which extends July 1, 2026 to June 30th, 2027.

24
00:07:53,769 --> 00:08:00,159
[SPEAKER_15]: Community Development Block Grant, CDBG, is a program of the United States Department of Housing and Urban Development, HUD, that began in 1974.

25
00:08:00,900 --> 00:08:07,009
[SPEAKER_15]: Fiscal year 27 will be the City of Medford's program year 52 of CDBG funding.

26
00:08:07,930 --> 00:08:08,631
[SPEAKER_15]: And we do have here...

27
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:13,562
[SPEAKER_15]: There will be a meeting of the Medford City Council Committee of the Whole on Tuesday, April 20, 2026 at 6 p.m.

28
00:08:13,602 --> 00:08:26,328
[SPEAKER_15]: The purpose of this meeting is to discuss the city's Community Development Block Grant Annual Action Plan for Program Year 2026, July 1, 2026 to June 30, 2027, and the public services applications for CDBG grant funding.

29
00:08:26,808 --> 00:08:31,150
[SPEAKER_15]: Copies of the plan are available for review and download at medfordma.org slash CDBG.

30
00:08:31,330 --> 00:08:35,772
[SPEAKER_15]: The Annual Action Plan contains the city's proposed use of CDBG grant funds for the program year.

31
00:08:36,252 --> 00:08:42,857
[SPEAKER_15]: City Council has invited Alicia Hunt, the Director of the Office of Planning, Development, and Sustainability, and Laurel Siegel, CDBG and Grants Manager to attend.

32
00:08:43,057 --> 00:08:46,599
[SPEAKER_15]: Representatives from the public services agencies applying for funds will also be in attendance.

33
00:08:47,220 --> 00:08:59,048
[SPEAKER_15]: If you need reasonable accommodation to attend or participate in this meeting, please contact the ADA Coordinator, Frances Nwaje, at 781-393-2439, or via email at fnwaje at medford-ma.gov.

34
00:08:59,529 --> 00:09:05,673
[SPEAKER_15]: Please note that while the city will make every effort to fulfill their requests, some requests may not be fulfilled due to the hiring and availability of outside contractors.

35
00:09:06,281 --> 00:09:07,682
[SPEAKER_15]: and Councilor Sang is present.

36
00:09:08,103 --> 00:09:14,848
[SPEAKER_15]: So I will turn this over to Laurel, our CDBG and Grants Manager, to share a little bit more and then we'll go through the applicants.

37
00:09:14,868 --> 00:09:17,170
[SPEAKER_03]: Great, thank you so much.

38
00:09:18,011 --> 00:09:27,219
[SPEAKER_03]: So yes, we're here to discuss our annual action plan and also for an opportunity for our public services grantees to describe their programs and answer any questions that you may have.

39
00:09:28,140 --> 00:09:33,665
[SPEAKER_03]: So we are a CDBG entitlement community, which means that we receive direct funding from HUD every year.

40
00:09:34,885 --> 00:09:39,386
[SPEAKER_03]: Our allocation for next year is about 1.433 million.

41
00:09:39,887 --> 00:09:44,968
[SPEAKER_03]: That does represent a reduction of about 32,000 or 2.2% from last year.

42
00:09:46,448 --> 00:09:50,169
[SPEAKER_03]: In addition, we have about 300,000 of unused prior year funds.

43
00:09:50,309 --> 00:09:55,291
[SPEAKER_03]: Those are just funds that for various reasons, projects get delayed or aren't requiring the full funds.

44
00:09:55,371 --> 00:09:57,971
[SPEAKER_03]: So our available funds for next year is 1.733 million.

45
00:10:01,512 --> 00:10:05,654
[SPEAKER_03]: And then we break that down into a couple of different buckets.

46
00:10:06,194 --> 00:10:13,297
[SPEAKER_03]: We are allowed to spend up to 20% of our annual allocation on planning and administration.

47
00:10:13,777 --> 00:10:18,079
[SPEAKER_03]: That largely goes to pay salaries for staff such as myself, our housing planner.

48
00:10:18,679 --> 00:10:21,622
[SPEAKER_03]: economic development planner and part of the PDS head clerk.

49
00:10:22,323 --> 00:10:30,791
[SPEAKER_03]: We're also allowed to allocate up to 15 percent of our annual allocation to public services and we do maximize that as much as we can.

50
00:10:31,411 --> 00:10:44,143
[SPEAKER_03]: And then the remainder goes into various projects parks projects roadways and econ development programs as well as housing programs such as our housing rehab loan program.

51
00:10:45,583 --> 00:10:52,525
[SPEAKER_03]: In the past, we did have CDBG CV or coronavirus funds, but those have now been fully expended.

52
00:10:52,565 --> 00:10:54,865
[SPEAKER_03]: So those are no longer included in the annual plan.

53
00:10:56,446 --> 00:11:03,608
[SPEAKER_03]: Unless there are any questions, I would love to just proceed to introducing some of our public services grantees.

54
00:11:06,468 --> 00:11:06,708
[SPEAKER_15]: Great.

55
00:11:07,609 --> 00:11:08,269
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you, Laurel.

56
00:11:09,089 --> 00:11:10,689
[SPEAKER_15]: We'll take them in order.

57
00:11:12,750 --> 00:11:13,690
[SPEAKER_15]: Cool if I use the table.

58
00:11:14,753 --> 00:11:15,113
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm sorry?

59
00:11:15,494 --> 00:11:16,975
[SPEAKER_15]: If I use the table for alphabetical?

60
00:11:16,995 --> 00:11:17,415
[SPEAKER_03]: Oh, yes, please do.

61
00:11:17,435 --> 00:11:17,576
[SPEAKER_03]: Great.

62
00:11:17,636 --> 00:11:22,260
[SPEAKER_03]: And we do, for ABCD, we do have Josh White in the room with us, so he can come and join me here.

63
00:11:22,280 --> 00:11:22,400
[SPEAKER_03]: Great.

64
00:11:22,420 --> 00:11:23,581
[SPEAKER_15]: We'll start with ABCD.

65
00:11:25,182 --> 00:11:27,585
[SPEAKER_14]: I love the fact that my organization is ABCD.

66
00:11:27,945 --> 00:11:29,086
[SPEAKER_14]: I get in and out for

67
00:11:30,008 --> 00:11:32,130
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you for the opportunity to speak with you folks tonight.

68
00:11:32,190 --> 00:11:33,571
[SPEAKER_14]: Again, my name is Joshua White.

69
00:11:33,711 --> 00:11:37,353
[SPEAKER_14]: I am the Director of Housing and Homelessness Prevention for ABCD.

70
00:11:37,934 --> 00:11:46,560
[SPEAKER_14]: I'm here today to talk to you about the Medford CDBG program and how it helps support Medford residents in preserving their housing.

71
00:11:47,140 --> 00:11:49,262
[SPEAKER_14]: Our program operates two ways.

72
00:11:49,542 --> 00:12:01,093
[SPEAKER_14]: First is our emergency financial program that works with Medford residents on ensuring that they are able to pay any back rental arrears or utility arrears.

73
00:12:01,824 --> 00:12:17,114
[SPEAKER_14]: And then we also provide housing counseling case management for those Medford residents, specifically our financial literacy program to ensure that Medford residents that find themselves in financial hardship have the tools and skills necessary to ensure that they become independent and self-sufficient.

74
00:12:18,936 --> 00:12:20,817
[SPEAKER_14]: So that is ABCD in a nutshell.

75
00:12:21,882 --> 00:12:28,944
[SPEAKER_14]: I also did want to add one quick thing that is not related to the Medford CDBG program, and that is we are coming to the end of our fuel assistance year.

76
00:12:29,564 --> 00:12:33,125
[SPEAKER_14]: Applications will be accepted until 1159 p.m.

77
00:12:33,605 --> 00:12:35,206
[SPEAKER_14]: on Thursday, April 30th.

78
00:12:35,226 --> 00:12:43,788
[SPEAKER_14]: So any of your constituents are looking for fuel assistance, please have them reach out to our offices or visit our fuel assistance office in Malden.

79
00:12:46,277 --> 00:12:46,557
[SPEAKER_15]: Great.

80
00:12:47,338 --> 00:12:47,758
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

81
00:12:47,918 --> 00:12:51,641
[SPEAKER_15]: Do we have any questions from members of the council around the ABCD proposal?

82
00:12:52,922 --> 00:12:53,782
[SPEAKER_15]: Councillor Scarpelli.

83
00:12:53,802 --> 00:13:03,990
[SPEAKER_11]: I'm glad you brought that up because this past week I've been working with an elderly young lady that lives in Medford that we realized very independent.

84
00:13:04,610 --> 00:13:06,932
[SPEAKER_11]: So finally she allowed her son to look into her

85
00:13:07,590 --> 00:13:18,317
[SPEAKER_11]: her finances and realized her last two months of heating was over $700 from a local oil company.

86
00:13:18,918 --> 00:13:20,539
[SPEAKER_11]: And that's one of the.

87
00:13:21,181 --> 00:13:28,784
[SPEAKER_11]: The first things that every advocate and supports members requested is reach out to ABC and they've been great.

88
00:13:28,804 --> 00:13:35,847
[SPEAKER_11]: So I just bring that forward just because it's real life when it, you know, I've seen it firsthand just a couple of days ago.

89
00:13:35,887 --> 00:13:36,947
[SPEAKER_11]: So we appreciate the work.

90
00:13:37,187 --> 00:13:37,827
[SPEAKER_11]: Absolutely.

91
00:13:37,988 --> 00:13:39,048
[SPEAKER_11]: So thank you, Mr. President.

92
00:13:39,548 --> 00:13:41,749
[SPEAKER_14]: And just to let folks know, we did move locations.

93
00:13:41,789 --> 00:13:47,091
[SPEAKER_14]: So the new fuel systems office is located at Florence Street, directly across the street from the mall and Center T Station.

94
00:13:48,672 --> 00:13:48,892
[SPEAKER_14]: Great.

95
00:13:49,172 --> 00:13:49,472
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you.

96
00:13:51,107 --> 00:13:54,289
[SPEAKER_15]: Any other questions for ABCD?

97
00:13:57,450 --> 00:13:57,870
[SPEAKER_15]: All right.

98
00:13:57,890 --> 00:14:01,532
[SPEAKER_15]: Seeing none, we'll move to the next item, housing families.

99
00:14:05,274 --> 00:14:05,534
[SPEAKER_15]: Great.

100
00:14:05,794 --> 00:14:07,035
[SPEAKER_15]: I'll recognize you, Jaina.

101
00:14:07,955 --> 00:14:08,495
[SPEAKER_07]: Hi, everyone.

102
00:14:08,515 --> 00:14:09,056
[SPEAKER_07]: Good evening.

103
00:14:09,076 --> 00:14:10,636
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you so much for having us here.

104
00:14:11,197 --> 00:14:13,037
[SPEAKER_07]: I wish that I were with you in person.

105
00:14:13,057 --> 00:14:16,199
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm a little under the weather today, which is why I'm on Zoom.

106
00:14:17,620 --> 00:14:22,984
[SPEAKER_07]: We have been located in the Tri-Cities area since 1991.

107
00:14:23,464 --> 00:14:25,565
[SPEAKER_07]: So our program, this is our 35th year.

108
00:14:26,366 --> 00:14:31,949
[SPEAKER_07]: We originally started out at the Tri-City Community Action Program, which would be a sister program to ABCD.

109
00:14:33,090 --> 00:14:38,273
[SPEAKER_07]: So when that program closed, we moved over to Housing Families in 2015.

110
00:14:38,653 --> 00:14:41,595
[SPEAKER_07]: So we have a long history of serving the Tri-City area.

111
00:14:42,435 --> 00:14:48,218
[SPEAKER_07]: And we are still the only legal services entity that is located here in the Tri-Cities.

112
00:14:49,879 --> 00:15:01,265
[SPEAKER_07]: We offer a full range of legal services, which includes legal advice, referrals, advocacy, limited assistance representation, full representation, and financial advocacy.

113
00:15:01,806 --> 00:15:07,829
[SPEAKER_07]: We find that combining legal services with financial assistance really makes the difference.

114
00:15:08,089 --> 00:15:11,451
[SPEAKER_07]: So we can get a lot done with not even always a lot of money.

115
00:15:11,571 --> 00:15:17,518
[SPEAKER_07]: but just a little bit can really, really help us kind of move the ball towards keeping the family stably housed.

116
00:15:18,278 --> 00:15:25,326
[SPEAKER_07]: And we work all along the points of someone that's stably housed, but has some concerns.

117
00:15:25,366 --> 00:15:32,274
[SPEAKER_07]: Maybe their landlord said that they're gonna be selling in a year, all the way through the constable is coming in the morning.

118
00:15:32,975 --> 00:15:41,189
[SPEAKER_07]: or we also have families sometimes who are unhoused, and we have advocacy services try to get them into emergency assistance.

119
00:15:43,390 --> 00:15:47,692
[SPEAKER_07]: The other services at Housing Families also help us deliver this holistic model.

120
00:15:47,852 --> 00:16:01,777
[SPEAKER_07]: We have our resource hub, we have clinical supports, our children's programming, we have permanent supportive housing, we have emergency shelter units that we contract with through HLC.

121
00:16:03,797 --> 00:16:12,522
[SPEAKER_07]: And we have our individual supports for, I don't want to say individuals again, but individuals experiencing homelessness.

122
00:16:12,562 --> 00:16:30,572
[SPEAKER_07]: So we have the shelter space, we have our street outreach team, and this full array really helps us deliver what anyone primarily could use to stabilize their tenancy and, or become housed if they are experiencing homelessness already.

123
00:16:32,215 --> 00:16:35,737
[SPEAKER_07]: In calendar year, I just pulled a little bit of data.

124
00:16:35,817 --> 00:16:49,061
[SPEAKER_07]: So in calendar year 2025, we were able to deliver $17,699 in rental assistance external from the city to the residents of Medford.

125
00:16:49,542 --> 00:16:54,643
[SPEAKER_07]: And I say external because we also participate with the Medford CPA program.

126
00:16:54,723 --> 00:16:58,705
[SPEAKER_07]: And that's been super helpful in offering that full array of services.

127
00:17:00,947 --> 00:17:03,368
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that's pretty much all I wanted to cover.

128
00:17:03,448 --> 00:17:06,329
[SPEAKER_07]: That's us also in a nutshell.

129
00:17:07,609 --> 00:17:12,471
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm happy to answer any questions or elaborate on anything if that's helpful.

130
00:17:14,331 --> 00:17:14,791
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

131
00:17:14,911 --> 00:17:16,812
[SPEAKER_15]: I'll go to Vice President Lazaro.

132
00:17:19,033 --> 00:17:19,473
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

133
00:17:20,713 --> 00:17:27,055
[SPEAKER_00]: I talk about the work that Housing Families does kind of a lot.

134
00:17:27,095 --> 00:17:28,356
[SPEAKER_00]: I really appreciate your work.

135
00:17:32,061 --> 00:17:41,449
[SPEAKER_00]: services that are provided by housing families, and this is true of ABCD too, are really critical, important services offered to very vulnerable residents in the region.

136
00:17:41,589 --> 00:17:47,274
[SPEAKER_00]: And these services are definitely used by Medford residents.

137
00:17:47,655 --> 00:17:54,180
[SPEAKER_00]: And that being said, especially homelessness is a regional issue because once you

138
00:17:55,121 --> 00:18:00,503
[SPEAKER_00]: are threatened to lose your home or you do lose your home, you become a resident of the area.

139
00:18:00,563 --> 00:18:03,924
[SPEAKER_00]: You find services where you can find them.

140
00:18:03,984 --> 00:18:19,069
[SPEAKER_00]: So these programs operate across this region, but I can say when I worked in Malden in this area, there were many Medford residents that utilized the services.

141
00:18:19,169 --> 00:18:23,191
[SPEAKER_00]: So I just wanted to say how important it is to

142
00:18:24,804 --> 00:18:29,534
[SPEAKER_00]: do the kind of work that, excuse me, I'm sorry, I missed your name.

143
00:18:32,488 --> 00:18:51,664
[SPEAKER_00]: that you were describing to try to catch people before they go fully into homelessness or if it's something where somebody might need legal assistance but wouldn't necessarily be able to afford it because sometimes that stuff snowballs and, you know, a few bills pile up and then suddenly, you know, people can't get out of it.

144
00:18:51,804 --> 00:18:57,508
[SPEAKER_00]: So, always, it's always easier to help somebody avoid falling into,

145
00:18:58,853 --> 00:19:01,714
[SPEAKER_00]: a trap like that than pulling somebody all the way out of it.

146
00:19:02,615 --> 00:19:08,217
[SPEAKER_00]: So I just wanted to say how critical that work is and how much we appreciate it here in Medford.

147
00:19:08,877 --> 00:19:10,798
[SPEAKER_00]: I was wondering if you could clarify for me something.

148
00:19:10,898 --> 00:19:18,922
[SPEAKER_00]: This grant, will it just support legal services or all of the work that Housing Families does for Medford residents?

149
00:19:19,808 --> 00:19:21,689
[SPEAKER_07]: This will be for our legal services program.

150
00:19:22,429 --> 00:19:25,310
[SPEAKER_07]: Our full name is Legal Aid for Wellbeing and Stability.

151
00:19:25,591 --> 00:19:35,815
[SPEAKER_07]: So we bring in those other supports as part of a holistic model of serving the entire person rather than just fixing a quick legal issue.

152
00:19:36,215 --> 00:19:38,056
[SPEAKER_07]: We want to know why they got behind.

153
00:19:38,076 --> 00:19:42,998
[SPEAKER_07]: Are they receiving everything that they can to help them be stable moving forward?

154
00:19:43,018 --> 00:19:44,479
[SPEAKER_00]: Great.

155
00:19:45,099 --> 00:19:45,419
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

156
00:19:46,540 --> 00:19:47,240
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you so much.

157
00:19:54,487 --> 00:19:54,927
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

158
00:19:55,067 --> 00:19:55,907
[SPEAKER_15]: Councilor Lemming.

159
00:19:57,688 --> 00:19:58,088
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

160
00:19:58,848 --> 00:20:21,713
[SPEAKER_13]: There was an incident that happened a couple of weeks ago, which I hope can just, for any other residents who might be watching, illustrate why some issues like homelessness, eviction, legal services around housing is necessary for this community.

161
00:20:21,753 --> 00:20:23,714
[SPEAKER_13]: I got a panicked call from a

162
00:20:24,594 --> 00:20:39,983
[SPEAKER_13]: from a resident, a fellow who I had canvassed during the election, saying that the apartment complex he was living in, a family had just suddenly been, like, literally half an hour before, evicted from their apartment building.

163
00:20:43,154 --> 00:20:51,099
[SPEAKER_13]: all of their belongings in about 60 boxes were literally inside the lobby and they didn't have a place to sleep that night.

164
00:20:51,859 --> 00:20:55,702
[SPEAKER_13]: And it was unfortunate.

165
00:20:55,942 --> 00:21:00,665
[SPEAKER_13]: And you know, that's not something that city councilors normally deal with.

166
00:21:00,725 --> 00:21:02,346
[SPEAKER_13]: And so I was great.

167
00:21:02,506 --> 00:21:03,506
[SPEAKER_13]: And so it was basically,

168
00:21:04,587 --> 00:21:08,972
[SPEAKER_13]: what we are left to do is to connect them to social services.

169
00:21:09,172 --> 00:21:12,635
[SPEAKER_13]: I connected this family with Jaina.

170
00:21:12,735 --> 00:21:14,117
[SPEAKER_13]: I reached out to her.

171
00:21:14,237 --> 00:21:22,685
[SPEAKER_13]: I connected them with some of the housing advocates I'd known that I'd worked with in the past.

172
00:21:22,845 --> 00:21:24,887
[SPEAKER_13]: When these things happen, and they do happen,

173
00:21:25,880 --> 00:21:30,606
[SPEAKER_13]: And you never know when it's going to happen, but it happens all the time.

174
00:21:30,646 --> 00:21:33,309
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm sure Jayna has plenty of experience of seeing this stuff.

175
00:21:34,190 --> 00:21:37,575
[SPEAKER_13]: You do need people who can handle this situation.

176
00:21:38,095 --> 00:21:44,003
[SPEAKER_13]: You do need people on the line when suddenly there's a family that just doesn't have any other place to go.

177
00:21:44,523 --> 00:21:48,225
[SPEAKER_13]: And so I'm glad to see the city putting some money.

178
00:21:48,925 --> 00:21:55,888
[SPEAKER_13]: I wish we could put more, but I'm glad to seeing us put some money towards services like housing families.

179
00:21:55,928 --> 00:22:05,993
[SPEAKER_13]: So once again, Jayna, thank you for all the work you put into your job and thank you so much to your organization for partnering with our city.

180
00:22:07,034 --> 00:22:07,814
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you so much.

181
00:22:07,834 --> 00:22:08,794
[SPEAKER_07]: I appreciate that.

182
00:22:10,195 --> 00:22:11,236
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you, Councilor Lemming.

183
00:22:11,276 --> 00:22:11,916
[SPEAKER_15]: Councilor Malauulu.

184
00:22:13,328 --> 00:22:16,669
[SPEAKER_01]: I also want to thank you for all of your hard work in this area.

185
00:22:16,809 --> 00:22:21,910
[SPEAKER_01]: I can only imagine the amount of people that are reaching out to you.

186
00:22:21,990 --> 00:22:28,392
[SPEAKER_01]: And I noticed in here you had said the program will assist an estimated 175 Medford residents.

187
00:22:28,412 --> 00:22:31,273
[SPEAKER_01]: I was just curious, kind of two questions on it.

188
00:22:31,353 --> 00:22:36,114
[SPEAKER_01]: Have you seen kind of a rising uptick in terms of the number of people reaching out to you?

189
00:22:37,314 --> 00:22:51,961
[SPEAKER_01]: If so, are there more than that 175 that you anticipate coming in for this next year that you'll probably need to give assistance to?

190
00:22:51,981 --> 00:22:58,044
[SPEAKER_07]: I started doing this work in 2006, and every year, I keep thinking this is the hardest year.

191
00:22:58,064 --> 00:23:03,166
[SPEAKER_07]: I wrote out that first foreclosure crisis in 2008 through 2010.

192
00:23:03,587 --> 00:23:06,248
[SPEAKER_07]: We saw COVID, we saw so many things.

193
00:23:07,503 --> 00:23:10,764
[SPEAKER_07]: We saw the rents just go sky high.

194
00:23:10,884 --> 00:23:16,487
[SPEAKER_07]: When I first came here, people were coming to our area because they couldn't afford like Cambridge or things like that.

195
00:23:16,567 --> 00:23:19,028
[SPEAKER_07]: And now it's so expensive.

196
00:23:19,088 --> 00:23:22,569
[SPEAKER_07]: So it continues to be very difficult for families.

197
00:23:23,449 --> 00:23:24,230
[SPEAKER_07]: So we see

198
00:23:25,670 --> 00:23:27,111
[SPEAKER_07]: A lot of people that need help.

199
00:23:27,292 --> 00:23:32,556
[SPEAKER_07]: And sometimes the issues become more and more serious, especially when there's job loss.

200
00:23:32,676 --> 00:23:35,778
[SPEAKER_07]: And then when you have a high rent plus job loss.

201
00:23:35,818 --> 00:23:37,740
[SPEAKER_07]: If you can't pay it just adds up so quickly.

202
00:23:38,280 --> 00:23:43,364
[SPEAKER_07]: And so we we try to stem it as early as we can and get people back on the right track.

203
00:23:44,105 --> 00:23:46,387
[SPEAKER_07]: But there is a lot of need out there right now.

204
00:23:47,310 --> 00:23:56,332
[SPEAKER_07]: There's a unique, the way our supports, our contracts and grants are layered, even when we do exceed a goal, we just keep working.

205
00:23:56,672 --> 00:24:00,353
[SPEAKER_07]: So we are able to, we have other grants that cover parts of things.

206
00:24:00,413 --> 00:24:06,674
[SPEAKER_07]: And so we're able to just keep working in our communities, even when we do exceed the number of people that we were expecting.

207
00:24:08,175 --> 00:24:08,535
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you.

208
00:24:09,315 --> 00:24:09,715
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you.

209
00:24:11,908 --> 00:24:12,388
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

210
00:24:12,408 --> 00:24:18,152
[SPEAKER_15]: Do we have any further questions for Jayna on the housing families proposal for CDBG funding?

211
00:24:21,313 --> 00:24:21,674
[SPEAKER_15]: Seeing none.

212
00:24:21,834 --> 00:24:22,474
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you, Jayna.

213
00:24:23,255 --> 00:24:24,275
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you all so much.

214
00:24:24,295 --> 00:24:25,176
[SPEAKER_07]: Pleasure to be here.

215
00:24:26,837 --> 00:24:32,460
[SPEAKER_15]: We'll move to the Medford Council on Aging and I see our director Pam Kelly.

216
00:24:32,780 --> 00:24:35,562
[SPEAKER_15]: So I will recognize you director Kelly.

217
00:24:37,845 --> 00:24:38,765
[SPEAKER_05]: Good evening, everybody.

218
00:24:38,805 --> 00:24:40,866
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm sorry I can't be in person tonight.

219
00:24:42,187 --> 00:24:49,311
[SPEAKER_05]: But I do, I'm very happy to be a continued recipient of the CDBG grant.

220
00:24:49,751 --> 00:24:55,854
[SPEAKER_05]: As you all know, the Medford City has a very high demographic of seniors age 60 and older.

221
00:24:56,494 --> 00:25:04,862
[SPEAKER_05]: We have over 12,744 people that are eligible to use the senior center's resources.

222
00:25:05,583 --> 00:25:11,128
[SPEAKER_05]: And not that we see all of them, but we want to make sure that they all know who we are and what we have.

223
00:25:11,488 --> 00:25:18,895
[SPEAKER_05]: This particular grant assists our social worker for additional hours so that she's able to outreach throughout the city of Medford

224
00:25:19,235 --> 00:25:28,379
[SPEAKER_05]: to get the people that are unable to come to the senior center, to meet them at their homes, and also to offer services even at the library.

225
00:25:29,380 --> 00:25:45,388
[SPEAKER_05]: The social worker works very close with many different resources in the city of Medford, whether it be with Jaina at housing, ABCD for oil, Mystic Valley Elder Services, and pretty much every department within the city.

226
00:25:46,208 --> 00:25:54,608
[SPEAKER_05]: The handyman that we do primarily, his role is to assist seniors to stay safe in their own home.

227
00:25:55,032 --> 00:26:12,044
[SPEAKER_05]: For example, climbing a six foot ladder to replace the smoke detectors or the batteries in them, putting curtain rods up, fixing stuck windows, replacing doorknobs, things to keep people safe in their home, handles.

228
00:26:13,345 --> 00:26:24,573
[SPEAKER_05]: And that has been increasing because we're making sure that we get the word out that that is a service that is available to all Medford residents, whether they're in a home or an apartment.

229
00:26:26,092 --> 00:26:31,036
[SPEAKER_05]: The third thing that we do offer with the grant is recreational transportation option.

230
00:26:31,696 --> 00:26:53,711
[SPEAKER_05]: So we do many day trips throughout the year, and we're able to reduce the price of the overall day trip with this transportation portion that will allow people to go on guided trips and tours, whether it be to North Shore Music Theater, to have a luncheon and a show, whether it's to a,

231
00:26:55,464 --> 00:26:59,688
[SPEAKER_05]: Blaster Cruise, or any, we have many different ones.

232
00:26:59,748 --> 00:27:04,033
[SPEAKER_05]: If you see our newsletter, you'll see that pretty much every month there's something different going on.

233
00:27:04,794 --> 00:27:13,903
[SPEAKER_05]: And we do assist approximately 50 people per trip, and we do, with the funding, about 10 trips per year.

234
00:27:14,884 --> 00:27:17,327
[SPEAKER_05]: Our final and fourth program,

235
00:27:18,853 --> 00:27:23,014
[SPEAKER_05]: program that we offer is the Mystic Valley Elder Services Title III match.

236
00:27:24,194 --> 00:27:38,538
[SPEAKER_05]: Many of you are aware Mystic Valley offers services to the Medford residents, whether it's meals on wheels, in-home services, guidance to keep them safe, in-home care,

237
00:27:39,879 --> 00:27:44,303
[SPEAKER_05]: this helps match that money, the funds that are due throughout the year.

238
00:27:44,663 --> 00:27:50,128
[SPEAKER_05]: And they do represent very close to 8,000 people a year in Medford.

239
00:27:51,369 --> 00:28:02,678
[SPEAKER_05]: So we are very grateful and thankful that the CDBG grant is available to the Medford Senior Center to offer those extra services that would not be covered normally through our regular funding.

240
00:28:04,059 --> 00:28:04,539
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

241
00:28:04,560 --> 00:28:07,122
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you, Pam.

242
00:28:07,162 --> 00:28:08,483
[SPEAKER_15]: Do we have any questions for

243
00:28:09,424 --> 00:28:12,385
[SPEAKER_15]: Pam, on the Medford Council on Aging proposal.

244
00:28:16,327 --> 00:28:17,608
[SPEAKER_15]: All right, seeing none.

245
00:28:17,628 --> 00:28:19,909
[SPEAKER_15]: Oh, Councilor Scarpelli.

246
00:28:20,729 --> 00:28:20,969
[SPEAKER_11]: Again.

247
00:28:20,989 --> 00:28:23,971
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you, Mr. President, and through the Chair.

248
00:28:24,651 --> 00:28:29,593
[SPEAKER_11]: Pam, as I mentioned, ABC did the fuel assistance.

249
00:28:30,174 --> 00:28:33,015
[SPEAKER_11]: I think the support that we have

250
00:28:33,697 --> 00:28:42,340
[SPEAKER_11]: from your department, your leadership, I think this is the connection that we received through your office, through this social worker.

251
00:28:42,440 --> 00:28:52,603
[SPEAKER_11]: And I think that it's so vital when you see the number of aging residents here in the city of Medford.

252
00:28:53,603 --> 00:28:59,145
[SPEAKER_11]: Has there been talk about increasing that position to a full-time position?

253
00:28:59,165 --> 00:29:00,826
[SPEAKER_11]: Because I'm sure we need it.

254
00:29:02,202 --> 00:29:15,713
[SPEAKER_11]: Again, like I said, this is a senior citizen who's a very independent person, but really needed support for her son who lived out of state.

255
00:29:16,238 --> 00:29:21,282
[SPEAKER_11]: and reaching out to a city councilor because they didn't know who to talk to at the time.

256
00:29:21,362 --> 00:29:42,617
[SPEAKER_11]: So my question again, first I want to thank you and your team for being there with such a small number of support staff, but is there any hope or wish that we can increase that position to a full-time position and maybe more?

257
00:29:43,404 --> 00:29:44,365
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you for the question.

258
00:29:44,945 --> 00:29:53,550
[SPEAKER_05]: Yes, actually, we did and have been able to increase her hours from 25 hours a week to 30 hours a week.

259
00:29:54,071 --> 00:29:58,593
[SPEAKER_05]: So it's a gradual process, but we'll be working on that as well.

260
00:29:59,634 --> 00:30:00,615
[SPEAKER_11]: OK, well, I thank you.

261
00:30:00,695 --> 00:30:07,319
[SPEAKER_11]: And again, I thank our colleagues that are supporting our senior citizens.

262
00:30:07,379 --> 00:30:09,420
[SPEAKER_11]: So again, thank you, Mr. President.

263
00:30:10,541 --> 00:30:10,941
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

264
00:30:11,061 --> 00:30:12,762
[SPEAKER_15]: And I believe we have you back tomorrow night.

265
00:30:13,265 --> 00:30:23,750
[SPEAKER_15]: yeah for your budget as well so we can get into that more absolutely thank you awesome all right we'll move on to the next we have medford public schools

266
00:30:31,133 --> 00:30:32,594
[SPEAKER_15]: Sure, if you could just say all of that again.

267
00:30:32,874 --> 00:30:34,775
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm sorry.

268
00:30:34,915 --> 00:30:41,838
[SPEAKER_03]: It looks like we do not have a representative from Medford Public Schools with us tonight, so I will go ahead and just read the description of their program that we're funding.

269
00:30:42,858 --> 00:30:50,142
[SPEAKER_03]: Funding from CDBG will provide much needed tuition assistance to up to 20 low income families who need after school care for their school age children.

270
00:30:50,762 --> 00:30:54,924
[SPEAKER_03]: Though tuition is kept affordable, some families still struggle to afford the cost of the program.

271
00:30:55,562 --> 00:31:06,189
[SPEAKER_03]: The consequence for families who cannot afford to send their children to after school programs can be detrimental if it means children are left unattended or unsupervised or that a caregiver cannot work.

272
00:31:06,670 --> 00:31:16,917
[SPEAKER_03]: The CDBG scholarships will serve as a safety net for families whose financial circumstances change, providing program continuity for children and keeping them in a safe, supportive environment.

273
00:31:19,432 --> 00:31:19,672
[SPEAKER_15]: Awesome.

274
00:31:20,553 --> 00:31:24,555
[SPEAKER_15]: Do we have any questions about that that you can answer, Laurel?

275
00:31:25,975 --> 00:31:28,696
[SPEAKER_03]: Likely not, but I'm happy to entertain them if there are questions.

276
00:31:28,717 --> 00:31:28,917
[SPEAKER_03]: Sure.

277
00:31:32,258 --> 00:31:32,618
[SPEAKER_15]: All right.

278
00:31:32,658 --> 00:31:36,020
[SPEAKER_15]: Seeing none, we'll move to the next item, Mystic Valley Elder Services.

279
00:31:36,900 --> 00:31:40,902
[SPEAKER_15]: And it looks like we have Carla here from Mystic Valley Elder Services.

280
00:31:42,523 --> 00:31:44,264
[SPEAKER_15]: If you want to share a bit more about your proposal.

281
00:31:45,171 --> 00:31:46,392
[SPEAKER_08]: Sure.

282
00:31:46,652 --> 00:31:48,594
[SPEAKER_08]: Good evening and thank you so much for having me.

283
00:31:48,874 --> 00:31:51,016
[SPEAKER_08]: I do apologize I'm not in person.

284
00:31:51,597 --> 00:31:56,541
[SPEAKER_08]: My little girl is on the way so I'm on home rest until that happens.

285
00:31:56,741 --> 00:31:59,544
[SPEAKER_08]: But I wanted to thank you so much.

286
00:32:00,324 --> 00:32:08,592
[SPEAKER_08]: I just wanted to thank City Council again for your time tonight and to thank Medford for its continued support in our nutrition program.

287
00:32:09,372 --> 00:32:21,958
[SPEAKER_08]: So our program is, I'm the director of nutrition Carla Matute and what we do is we deliver home delivered meals to 11 cities and towns and to the residents of Medford, older adults and adults living with disabilities.

288
00:32:22,538 --> 00:32:25,999
[SPEAKER_08]: We also provide congregate dining sites in the city of Medford.

289
00:32:26,860 --> 00:32:33,943
[SPEAKER_08]: We support the dining site that is run through the Medford COA by the amazing Pam Paley and the amazing community that she's built.

290
00:32:34,590 --> 00:32:35,371
[SPEAKER_08]: at her center.

291
00:32:36,392 --> 00:32:41,777
[SPEAKER_08]: Really, we are in crucial times as a lot of programs are dealing with our seniors.

292
00:32:42,979 --> 00:32:49,846
[SPEAKER_08]: Due to the federal cuts, we have seen a reduction of 30% in federal funding and nutrition funding.

293
00:32:50,571 --> 00:32:58,954
[SPEAKER_08]: which has created a significant service gap, which leads us to requesting the 10,000 to help stabilize this program for us.

294
00:32:59,774 --> 00:33:05,416
[SPEAKER_08]: In the last year, we've delivered over 71,000 meals to older adults in the city of Medford.

295
00:33:06,857 --> 00:33:14,340
[SPEAKER_08]: What we really try and do in our program is not just serve a meal, but we provide wellness checks and socializations.

296
00:33:14,880 --> 00:33:17,521
[SPEAKER_08]: We provide emergency shelf stable meals for when we have

297
00:33:18,397 --> 00:33:19,538
[SPEAKER_08]: any winter storm.

298
00:33:19,598 --> 00:33:22,420
[SPEAKER_08]: This winter was, we were not prepared.

299
00:33:22,440 --> 00:33:25,061
[SPEAKER_08]: I don't think any of us had had a winter this past quite some time.

300
00:33:25,121 --> 00:33:45,374
[SPEAKER_08]: So it was really essential and crucial that we were able to supply so many shelf-stable meals to ensure that for all the closings that we had due to the conditions out there that our older adults were safe, had food and whatever necessary to make sure that they had the nutritional support they required until we were back on the road with them.

301
00:33:45,875 --> 00:33:47,936
[SPEAKER_08]: And we really value our partnership with the City of Medford.

302
00:33:49,012 --> 00:33:51,694
[SPEAKER_08]: and respectfully ask for your continued support in this program.

303
00:33:51,714 --> 00:33:58,879
[SPEAKER_08]: We do see that our program is proven and accountable.

304
00:33:58,899 --> 00:34:09,527
[SPEAKER_08]: More than 95% of the individuals we serve are low or moderate income, and annual consumer surveys show that participants are healthier and better able to remain living independently because of these services.

305
00:34:10,288 --> 00:34:16,132
[SPEAKER_08]: We currently do not have a wait list for Meals on Wheels, but there are wait lists in the state home care programs at this time.

306
00:34:16,839 --> 00:34:22,901
[SPEAKER_08]: which means we are serving Meals on Wheels system consumers who are looking for more services and supports in their homes.

307
00:34:22,961 --> 00:34:39,888
[SPEAKER_08]: And we really want to prevent there ever being a wait list for our program and services, because at least in interim where consumers are waiting for supports, they're able to receive a meal, a daily safety check, and ensure that they're being followed through Mystic Valley until we are able to get them off the wait list.

308
00:34:40,648 --> 00:34:42,549
[SPEAKER_08]: So that's just a little bit about our program.

309
00:34:43,189 --> 00:34:44,490
[SPEAKER_08]: Are there any questions that I could answer?

310
00:34:47,758 --> 00:34:48,039
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

311
00:34:48,059 --> 00:34:53,133
[SPEAKER_15]: Do we have any questions for Carla about the Mystic Valley Elder Services CDBG funding?

312
00:34:54,417 --> 00:34:55,039
[SPEAKER_15]: Councilor Malauulu.

313
00:34:56,397 --> 00:34:57,897
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't have any questions.

314
00:34:57,957 --> 00:35:01,178
[SPEAKER_01]: I just want to say thank you very much for all of your work.

315
00:35:01,978 --> 00:35:17,901
[SPEAKER_01]: I know quite a few people who utilize your services, and certainly when you mentioned not only getting meal service delivery, but it's also the socialization and being able to have contact with people throughout the day has been a really important and critical piece to it as well.

316
00:35:18,181 --> 00:35:25,342
[SPEAKER_01]: And I just, again, just want to thank you for your work and being able to serve as many people as you do.

317
00:35:26,122 --> 00:35:35,365
[SPEAKER_01]: I know that we're continuing to see this rise, and knowing that we have your services is, I know, puts me at ease, because I know, personally, people that have utilized your services.

318
00:35:35,425 --> 00:35:35,946
[SPEAKER_01]: So thank you.

319
00:35:37,686 --> 00:35:38,467
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you so much.

320
00:35:39,907 --> 00:35:40,287
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

321
00:35:40,347 --> 00:35:41,268
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you, Councilor Mullane.

322
00:35:41,288 --> 00:35:43,648
[SPEAKER_15]: All right.

323
00:35:43,709 --> 00:35:50,251
[SPEAKER_15]: I'm not seeing any further questions, so we'll move on to our next item, the Mystic Valley YMCA and Medford Community Market.

324
00:35:50,291 --> 00:35:50,871
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you, Carla.

325
00:35:51,551 --> 00:35:51,972
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

326
00:35:55,313 --> 00:35:55,633
[SPEAKER_15]: All right.

327
00:35:56,805 --> 00:36:00,167
[SPEAKER_15]: I will go to Lisa from the Mystic Valley YMCA.

328
00:36:00,287 --> 00:36:04,249
[SPEAKER_15]: Lisa, let us know a bit about your program and how this will support the Mystic Community Market.

329
00:36:05,269 --> 00:36:06,830
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes, thank you for the opportunity.

330
00:36:08,111 --> 00:36:16,655
[SPEAKER_02]: The Mystic Community Market opened in early 2020 at the Walnut Street Center on Mystic Ave, and it's the largest free food market in the area.

331
00:36:17,255 --> 00:36:20,337
[SPEAKER_02]: It's become a vital food access resource for Medford residents.

332
00:36:21,177 --> 00:36:23,238
[SPEAKER_02]: In the past year, we've served nearly 5,000 residents.

333
00:36:25,144 --> 00:36:37,974
[SPEAKER_02]: We've distributed 1.5 million pounds of food in the past year alone, and each visit to the market results in fresh produce, lean protein, dairy, and shelf-stable items.

334
00:36:39,575 --> 00:36:49,503
[SPEAKER_02]: One in five Medford residents currently struggles with food insecurity, and food insecurity impacts people across income, not just people below poverty guidelines.

335
00:36:50,314 --> 00:36:57,698
[SPEAKER_02]: Rising food costs and inflation continue to push more families into need, and we've seen that dramatically this past year.

336
00:36:59,379 --> 00:37:03,362
[SPEAKER_02]: Nearly 100% of our shoppers are low or very low income.

337
00:37:04,462 --> 00:37:07,784
[SPEAKER_02]: One third of the people who benefit from the market are children.

338
00:37:08,945 --> 00:37:16,510
[SPEAKER_02]: And 79% are members of historically underrepresented communities, including newcomers and first-generation Americans.

339
00:37:17,510 --> 00:37:18,831
[SPEAKER_02]: We're open six days a week,

340
00:37:19,284 --> 00:37:21,826
[SPEAKER_02]: We offer both appointments and drop-in access.

341
00:37:22,727 --> 00:37:33,335
[SPEAKER_02]: We deliver weekly groceries deliveries to 135 homebound seniors through partnerships with Medford Housing Authority and Medford Council on Aging.

342
00:37:34,476 --> 00:37:40,220
[SPEAKER_02]: And CDBG funds supports core operating costs, which makes this work possible.

343
00:37:41,822 --> 00:37:47,586
[SPEAKER_02]: Our short-term goal is to ensure consistent access to healthy supplemental food for the residents of Medford.

344
00:37:48,209 --> 00:37:57,411
[SPEAKER_02]: And our long-term goal is really to connect individuals to the services and opportunities that they need so that food assistance is no longer needed at some point.

345
00:37:58,551 --> 00:38:09,474
[SPEAKER_02]: The MISD community market is a proven effective response to food insecurity in Medford and continued CDBG support is essential to sustaining and expanding our impact.

346
00:38:10,194 --> 00:38:14,375
[SPEAKER_02]: And we want to thank you for your partnership and commitment to the health and wellbeing of our community.

347
00:38:15,175 --> 00:38:15,515
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

348
00:38:18,345 --> 00:38:18,725
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

349
00:38:18,745 --> 00:38:22,587
[SPEAKER_15]: Do we have any questions for Lisa about domestic community market funding?

350
00:38:24,228 --> 00:38:25,009
[SPEAKER_15]: Councilor Callahan.

351
00:38:26,770 --> 00:38:27,170
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

352
00:38:28,070 --> 00:38:35,634
[SPEAKER_10]: I have to say I love these CPG meetings because you find out about so many like truly remarkable programs that serve our community.

353
00:38:35,674 --> 00:38:37,115
[SPEAKER_10]: And I'm just curious about this one.

354
00:38:37,175 --> 00:38:39,236
[SPEAKER_10]: How do you reach out to people?

355
00:38:39,336 --> 00:38:44,959
[SPEAKER_10]: How do you, you know, what's the way that you identify the folks that need your services the most?

356
00:38:45,179 --> 00:38:45,440
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

357
00:38:47,100 --> 00:38:47,260
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes.

358
00:38:48,918 --> 00:38:51,459
[SPEAKER_02]: rely on referrals from other community agencies.

359
00:38:51,899 --> 00:38:54,920
[SPEAKER_02]: Um, we advertise through our membership.

360
00:38:55,360 --> 00:38:58,801
[SPEAKER_02]: Um, we, but we have a lot of partnerships.

361
00:38:58,881 --> 00:39:04,323
[SPEAKER_02]: So we, we partner with, um, Medford schools, Medford housing, elder services.

362
00:39:04,343 --> 00:39:09,484
[SPEAKER_02]: We have lots of community community partners, um, who, you know, help us spread the word.

363
00:39:13,966 --> 00:39:14,326
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

364
00:39:15,370 --> 00:39:16,871
[SPEAKER_15]: I'm seeing no further questions.

365
00:39:17,131 --> 00:39:18,211
[SPEAKER_15]: Lisa, thank you so much.

366
00:39:18,631 --> 00:39:20,512
[SPEAKER_15]: And we're going to move on to our next item.

367
00:39:23,873 --> 00:39:26,413
[SPEAKER_15]: All right, we've RISE Multicultural Services.

368
00:39:26,473 --> 00:39:28,414
[SPEAKER_15]: Is there, is that Monica?

369
00:39:28,454 --> 00:39:29,294
[SPEAKER_15]: Are you here from RISE?

370
00:39:30,995 --> 00:39:32,915
[SPEAKER_15]: All right, Monica, I'll ask you to unmute.

371
00:39:36,696 --> 00:39:37,457
[SPEAKER_04]: Hi, everyone.

372
00:39:38,717 --> 00:39:41,958
[SPEAKER_04]: It's always nice to see people from Medford.

373
00:39:43,176 --> 00:39:46,281
[SPEAKER_04]: My name is Monica and I'm here to represent RISE.

374
00:39:46,622 --> 00:39:52,293
[SPEAKER_04]: This project focuses on expanding multilingual mental health support circle.

375
00:39:52,780 --> 00:40:01,666
[SPEAKER_04]: for low and moderate income resident in Medford with a strong emphasis on senior and especially immigrant community.

376
00:40:02,247 --> 00:40:12,654
[SPEAKER_04]: Right now, many of those people seeking support are older adults who live alone, rely on fixed income like social security,

377
00:40:13,655 --> 00:40:22,864
[SPEAKER_04]: or nothing, and face barriers like language, transportation, and stigma around traditional mental health care.

378
00:40:23,585 --> 00:40:32,574
[SPEAKER_04]: Because of this, many don't feel comfortable accessing clinical services, but they are open to community-based

379
00:40:33,463 --> 00:40:37,166
[SPEAKER_04]: here support groups offered in their own language.

380
00:40:38,368 --> 00:40:56,024
[SPEAKER_04]: We have seen a growing demand for those groups, and currently our sessions are full with awaiting lists, mostly immigrant seniors experiencing isolation, anxiety, and emotional distress, especially what was going on with ICE.

381
00:40:57,245 --> 00:40:58,106
[SPEAKER_04]: With this funding,

382
00:40:58,782 --> 00:41:07,927
[SPEAKER_04]: We plan to expand the program by increasing meetings from monthly to weekly, which is especially important for seniors.

383
00:41:09,367 --> 00:41:20,093
[SPEAKER_04]: Regular, consistent support helps reduce isolation, improve emotional well-being, and build a sense of community and stability.

384
00:41:21,337 --> 00:41:25,319
[SPEAKER_04]: The support circle provides safe space for conversation.

385
00:41:25,599 --> 00:41:29,460
[SPEAKER_04]: They feel okay to talk to us, to be in a small group.

386
00:41:30,461 --> 00:41:34,022
[SPEAKER_04]: Copying strategies and connecting to others.

387
00:41:34,522 --> 00:41:42,145
[SPEAKER_04]: Essential services like housing, food, and healthcare, so we refer them to the other organization.

388
00:41:43,383 --> 00:41:51,970
[SPEAKER_04]: The goal of RISE is to create a presentative impact, reducing loneliness, improving mental health.

389
00:41:52,393 --> 00:42:05,616
[SPEAKER_04]: and helping residents stay engaged and stable in their community before issue become crisis and be able to introduce the resources available for them, like the senior center.

390
00:42:06,157 --> 00:42:09,197
[SPEAKER_04]: We do a lot, send them a lot there.

391
00:42:10,058 --> 00:42:15,639
[SPEAKER_04]: Overall, this project directly support low income and senior residents.

392
00:42:16,241 --> 00:42:25,525
[SPEAKER_04]: removes cultural and language barriers, and strengthens the wellbeing of some Medford most vulnerable population.

393
00:42:26,586 --> 00:42:38,511
[SPEAKER_04]: One thing I wanna share with you, when we have those people, we have something with the Haitian community, they don't like to talk about healthcare.

394
00:42:39,292 --> 00:42:41,533
[SPEAKER_04]: So when they are with us, they feel comfortable.

395
00:42:42,630 --> 00:42:47,580
[SPEAKER_04]: they can express themselves and our meeting doesn't have to be the agenda.

396
00:42:48,001 --> 00:42:52,029
[SPEAKER_04]: We not follow the agenda all the time because it depends on what's going on.

397
00:42:53,072 --> 00:42:57,214
[SPEAKER_04]: Like it's war going on and then they worry about it and we talk about it.

398
00:42:57,694 --> 00:43:01,696
[SPEAKER_04]: If somebody has somebody who lost and loves one, we talk about it.

399
00:43:01,816 --> 00:43:03,816
[SPEAKER_04]: And then sometime we came in, we play games.

400
00:43:04,297 --> 00:43:07,698
[SPEAKER_04]: So they enjoyed it and then they want to come.

401
00:43:07,798 --> 00:43:10,159
[SPEAKER_04]: We want to have more people and do it more often.

402
00:43:10,559 --> 00:43:12,860
[SPEAKER_04]: And I thank you for that grant.

403
00:43:13,140 --> 00:43:15,521
[SPEAKER_04]: And I thank the city of Medford for that grant.

404
00:43:15,581 --> 00:43:19,703
[SPEAKER_04]: So which that will allow us to have more meetings and more people.

405
00:43:20,103 --> 00:43:20,443
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

406
00:43:22,952 --> 00:43:23,592
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you, Monica.

407
00:43:23,612 --> 00:43:25,393
[SPEAKER_15]: And I want to thank you for all the work that you're doing.

408
00:43:26,234 --> 00:43:28,855
[SPEAKER_15]: You know, you're a new applicant this year.

409
00:43:29,115 --> 00:43:38,620
[SPEAKER_15]: And so our first chance to hear from you, many of the other folks we've worked with in the past and heard from, but really appreciate the work and the services that you're providing to our community.

410
00:43:39,440 --> 00:43:39,961
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

411
00:43:40,081 --> 00:43:40,501
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

412
00:43:41,582 --> 00:43:41,882
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

413
00:43:41,902 --> 00:43:46,724
[SPEAKER_15]: Do we have any other questions for Monica and the RISE Multicultural Services proposal?

414
00:43:46,764 --> 00:43:48,005
[SPEAKER_15]: I'll go to Vice President Lazaro.

415
00:43:49,688 --> 00:43:51,369
[SPEAKER_00]: Hi, I do have a question about RISE.

416
00:43:51,609 --> 00:43:53,590
[SPEAKER_00]: Are you located in Medford Square?

417
00:43:53,610 --> 00:43:54,930
[SPEAKER_00]: Do you have an office in Medford?

418
00:43:55,971 --> 00:43:56,691
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes, we do.

419
00:43:56,851 --> 00:44:01,973
[SPEAKER_04]: We are on 11 Salem Street and Suite 11 on the third floor.

420
00:44:03,013 --> 00:44:05,354
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, I think I came to a ribbon cutting for your office.

421
00:44:05,374 --> 00:44:07,295
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes, yes, I remember.

422
00:44:07,455 --> 00:44:08,375
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes, I saw you.

423
00:44:08,415 --> 00:44:09,156
[SPEAKER_04]: I remember that.

424
00:44:09,256 --> 00:44:09,436
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes.

425
00:44:09,860 --> 00:44:32,432
[SPEAKER_00]: You opened very recently, and I remember learning about your organization and how I was so excited about it because you offer translation services, and you're open in the evening when people get off work, and you do all this wonderful work for newly arrived people in this area who have—like, the people who are speaking these languages, the most common languages in Medford are not necessarily—what's going on?

426
00:44:32,972 --> 00:44:33,893
[SPEAKER_00]: We're losing our lights, sorry.

427
00:44:33,933 --> 00:44:34,933
[SPEAKER_00]: We're being so exciting.

428
00:44:36,895 --> 00:44:38,756
[SPEAKER_00]: The lights are turning off.

429
00:44:39,216 --> 00:44:58,789
[SPEAKER_00]: The languages that we need translations for are not necessarily the languages you would expect, but your organization is really meeting our residents where they are, and I'm so excited to hear that you're doing so much mental and behavioral health work because, of course,

430
00:44:59,537 --> 00:45:07,700
[SPEAKER_00]: it would be so critical for somebody, especially older people who are, you know, hearing about things that are happening back home.

431
00:45:08,000 --> 00:45:09,300
[SPEAKER_00]: Just so much important work.

432
00:45:09,380 --> 00:45:13,982
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm so grateful for the fact that you're doing that and that things are going well in your office space.

433
00:45:14,022 --> 00:45:15,683
[SPEAKER_00]: So I'm very glad to hear that.

434
00:45:15,703 --> 00:45:16,183
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

435
00:45:16,283 --> 00:45:16,683
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

436
00:45:16,723 --> 00:45:17,763
[SPEAKER_04]: That's mean a lot to us.

437
00:45:17,823 --> 00:45:18,624
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you so much.

438
00:45:18,644 --> 00:45:19,504
[SPEAKER_00]: Good.

439
00:45:22,445 --> 00:45:22,905
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

440
00:45:24,106 --> 00:45:26,967
[SPEAKER_15]: Seeing no further questions for RISE Multicultural Services.

441
00:45:27,267 --> 00:45:27,947
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you, Monica.

442
00:45:28,840 --> 00:45:29,341
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

443
00:45:30,783 --> 00:45:33,588
[SPEAKER_15]: We'll move to SCM Community Transport.

444
00:45:34,810 --> 00:45:36,794
[SPEAKER_15]: And I will recognize you at the podium.

445
00:45:39,378 --> 00:45:41,101
[SPEAKER_03]: We have John Keegan here from SCM.

446
00:45:42,869 --> 00:45:43,329
[SPEAKER_09]: Hi, folks.

447
00:45:43,569 --> 00:45:45,791
[SPEAKER_09]: Thanks for having all of us here.

448
00:45:45,871 --> 00:45:53,275
[SPEAKER_09]: And it always reminds me what a great nonprofit community we have in these local areas.

449
00:45:53,375 --> 00:45:54,316
[SPEAKER_09]: So it's good.

450
00:45:55,496 --> 00:46:02,841
[SPEAKER_09]: So SCM provides transportation primarily to seniors and some folks with various disabilities.

451
00:46:03,541 --> 00:46:05,162
[SPEAKER_09]: We focus mostly on

452
00:46:06,763 --> 00:46:09,525
[SPEAKER_09]: hospital visits, doctor's visits, et cetera.

453
00:46:09,866 --> 00:46:11,727
[SPEAKER_09]: We also do food shopping.

454
00:46:12,768 --> 00:46:21,975
[SPEAKER_09]: You know, behind the scenes, we kind of think we help people maintain a presence in the community through our clunky and big white vans.

455
00:46:22,836 --> 00:46:29,822
[SPEAKER_09]: And so we, what did I want to say about that?

456
00:46:30,949 --> 00:46:34,530
[SPEAKER_09]: We really don't have a great deal of excess capacity.

457
00:46:35,391 --> 00:46:43,033
[SPEAKER_09]: We don't hardly need to advertise because we pretty much overshoot our contracts every year.

458
00:46:43,053 --> 00:46:45,734
[SPEAKER_09]: This year we're doing that also.

459
00:46:46,955 --> 00:46:48,515
[SPEAKER_09]: I wanted to mention one thing.

460
00:46:50,605 --> 00:46:58,335
[SPEAKER_09]: an unusual grant from MassDOT, Mass Department of Transportation, to extend some of what we've been able to do.

461
00:46:58,956 --> 00:47:07,267
[SPEAKER_09]: And I was just looking at what we were able to do in Medford, and we have a couple things that we're doing here.

462
00:47:07,890 --> 00:47:16,237
[SPEAKER_09]: A little hard to read on my phone, but so we did an additional 148 shopping trips.

463
00:47:16,877 --> 00:47:25,003
[SPEAKER_09]: We started a shuttle to Target and Walmart because people were looking for a shuttle to Target and Walmart.

464
00:47:25,744 --> 00:47:33,950
[SPEAKER_09]: I've been working with Laurel on the Transportation Committee for a year, a year and a half or so, so some of the things come through those discussions.

465
00:47:36,559 --> 00:47:43,968
[SPEAKER_09]: So the Target shuttle and the Walmart shuttle have brought about 512 additional rides that were unfunded.

466
00:47:44,048 --> 00:47:45,690
[SPEAKER_09]: So they are funded through MassDOT.

467
00:47:46,110 --> 00:47:50,996
[SPEAKER_09]: So they didn't cost anything to the Medford CDBG contract.

468
00:47:52,678 --> 00:47:53,699
[SPEAKER_09]: In addition to that,

469
00:47:54,977 --> 00:48:03,861
[SPEAKER_09]: We've been able to do a little bit of social transportation, hairdressers, the places that seniors want to go.

470
00:48:04,782 --> 00:48:06,703
[SPEAKER_09]: All of our folks are low income.

471
00:48:07,904 --> 00:48:12,586
[SPEAKER_09]: And basically, they can't transport alone.

472
00:48:12,766 --> 00:48:14,607
[SPEAKER_09]: So we do a door-to-door service.

473
00:48:15,127 --> 00:48:23,631
[SPEAKER_09]: So our folks basically walk up to the front door, take arms, walk to the van, get people seated, clip on seatbelts, et cetera.

474
00:48:24,932 --> 00:48:27,555
[SPEAKER_09]: And finally, there was one other item.

475
00:48:28,736 --> 00:48:36,884
[SPEAKER_09]: In MedFed, we did an additional 170 medical trips under the MassDOT contract.

476
00:48:37,325 --> 00:48:43,791
[SPEAKER_09]: Again, these are over and above and to the side of the CDBG funding.

477
00:48:44,972 --> 00:48:49,634
[SPEAKER_09]: SCM's been doing transportation in Medford since 1981.

478
00:48:50,374 --> 00:49:00,077
[SPEAKER_09]: Not that I've been there since 1981, but the M in SCM is Medford, so Medford was one of the founding cities.

479
00:49:01,958 --> 00:49:07,140
[SPEAKER_09]: So, I guess, we also do one other thing that doesn't come through CDBG.

480
00:49:07,200 --> 00:49:17,343
[SPEAKER_09]: We do trips to adult day health facilities, and that's about half of what we do, usually in the morning and the late afternoon.

481
00:49:20,503 --> 00:49:20,744
[SPEAKER_15]: Great.

482
00:49:21,404 --> 00:49:21,904
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

483
00:49:21,964 --> 00:49:25,645
[SPEAKER_15]: Do we have any questions on the SCM community transport proposal?

484
00:49:30,020 --> 00:49:31,341
[SPEAKER_15]: All right, seeing none, thank you.

485
00:49:31,361 --> 00:49:32,181
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you for having me.

486
00:49:32,601 --> 00:49:35,302
[SPEAKER_15]: We'll close it out with the welcome project.

487
00:49:39,324 --> 00:49:42,265
[SPEAKER_15]: Oh, I see a couple people here from welcome.

488
00:49:43,405 --> 00:49:50,488
[SPEAKER_15]: And I'll recognize you if you want to present on the ESOL program that you are working on this year.

489
00:49:52,849 --> 00:49:53,309
[SPEAKER_06]: Hi, everyone.

490
00:49:53,489 --> 00:49:55,290
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you so much for the opportunity to speak tonight.

491
00:49:55,410 --> 00:49:56,591
[SPEAKER_06]: My name is Mary Beauchard.

492
00:49:56,891 --> 00:49:59,532
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm the ESL program coordinator at the Welcome Project.

493
00:50:00,112 --> 00:50:02,514
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm here with my colleague Suwani Lima tonight.

494
00:50:03,494 --> 00:50:07,876
[SPEAKER_06]: CDBG funding is used at the Welcome Project to support our English for Parents program.

495
00:50:08,817 --> 00:50:12,038
[SPEAKER_06]: This is one of three programs that we offer that serve immigrant residents.

496
00:50:12,739 --> 00:50:16,400
[SPEAKER_06]: This program is held in collaboration with the Medford public school system.

497
00:50:16,941 --> 00:50:21,763
[SPEAKER_06]: Our classes are beginner level classes open to parents and caregivers of children in the school system.

498
00:50:23,298 --> 00:50:27,002
[SPEAKER_06]: These classes are held in person and online to best accommodate parent schedules.

499
00:50:27,903 --> 00:50:33,709
[SPEAKER_06]: Our classes use a standard ESL curriculum, but also focus on navigating the school system, learning how to advocate for your children.

500
00:50:34,699 --> 00:50:35,539
[SPEAKER_06]: finding resources.

501
00:50:36,480 --> 00:50:38,161
[SPEAKER_06]: Parents want to be able to support their children.

502
00:50:38,421 --> 00:50:43,924
[SPEAKER_06]: This program empowers Medford parents to take an active role in not just their child's education, but also their community.

503
00:50:44,444 --> 00:50:52,949
[SPEAKER_06]: Through English for Parents classes, our students gain comfort speaking up at parent-teacher conferences, participating in school board meetings, and engaging in other school-related events.

504
00:50:53,669 --> 00:50:58,411
[SPEAKER_06]: Our EFP classes are taught by experienced teachers, and CDBG funding is used to compensate these educators.

505
00:50:59,252 --> 00:51:01,253
[SPEAKER_06]: At the Welcome Project, we also have an ESOL

506
00:51:01,837 --> 00:51:04,619
[SPEAKER_06]: a broader ESOL program, and a youth interpretation program.

507
00:51:05,659 --> 00:51:08,121
[SPEAKER_06]: As an organization, our work extends beyond education.

508
00:51:09,141 --> 00:51:17,466
[SPEAKER_06]: Much of what we do is supporting students outside of the classroom by connecting them with resources and local social services in areas like housing, legal support, food access, and more.

509
00:51:18,407 --> 00:51:20,128
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you for your continued support of our program.

510
00:51:23,890 --> 00:51:24,511
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you, Mary.

511
00:51:25,291 --> 00:51:26,592
[SPEAKER_15]: Swanee, is there anything you'd like to add?

512
00:51:29,850 --> 00:51:33,795
[SPEAKER_16]: I would like to extend my thank you for this program.

513
00:51:34,075 --> 00:51:36,558
[SPEAKER_16]: It's been helping a lot of immigrant parents.

514
00:51:37,139 --> 00:51:37,479
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you.

515
00:51:38,841 --> 00:51:39,221
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

516
00:51:39,261 --> 00:51:39,702
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you both.

517
00:51:39,722 --> 00:51:43,447
[SPEAKER_15]: Do we have any questions for Mary and Suani from the Welcome Project?

518
00:51:46,050 --> 00:51:46,270
[SPEAKER_15]: All right.

519
00:51:46,663 --> 00:51:49,247
[SPEAKER_15]: Seeing none, thank you, and I'll turn it back over to Laurel.

520
00:51:49,607 --> 00:51:52,691
[SPEAKER_15]: I think that's all of our projects, so if you want to close us out.

521
00:51:52,892 --> 00:51:53,572
[SPEAKER_15]: Did I miss anyone?

522
00:51:54,073 --> 00:51:54,934
[SPEAKER_03]: No, that was everybody.

523
00:51:54,954 --> 00:51:55,715
[SPEAKER_03]: Great.

524
00:51:55,836 --> 00:52:02,645
[SPEAKER_03]: So yeah, that was everybody, and the plan is available for public comment through May 13th.

525
00:52:04,666 --> 00:52:10,108
[SPEAKER_03]: And you can download a copy of the plan at medfordma.org slash CDBG.

526
00:52:10,148 --> 00:52:11,828
[SPEAKER_03]: We have our own CDBG webpage.

527
00:52:12,468 --> 00:52:16,629
[SPEAKER_03]: There is also a link on that page to a form for submitting comments.

528
00:52:17,290 --> 00:52:23,571
[SPEAKER_03]: But people can also submit comments by email directly to me at lseagle at medford-ma.gov.

529
00:52:24,291 --> 00:52:26,812
[SPEAKER_03]: So unless there are any other questions, that's everything I have to present.

530
00:52:27,269 --> 00:52:27,509
[SPEAKER_15]: Great.

531
00:52:27,669 --> 00:52:28,250
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you, Laurel.

532
00:52:28,270 --> 00:52:36,878
[SPEAKER_15]: Do we have any questions from members of the Council for Manager Laurel Siegel before we go to public participation and then close this meeting?

533
00:52:40,661 --> 00:52:46,607
[SPEAKER_15]: Seeing no questions from the Council, are there any members of the public, either in person or on Zoom, who'd like to speak at this time about our CDBG Action Plan?

534
00:52:51,206 --> 00:52:56,601
[SPEAKER_15]: Seeing none, is there a motion to report this to our regular meeting on May 12th?

535
00:52:56,942 --> 00:52:57,925
[SPEAKER_03]: May 12th.

536
00:52:57,985 --> 00:52:59,369
[SPEAKER_15]: That's when we'll take our final vote on this.

537
00:53:00,390 --> 00:53:07,574
[SPEAKER_15]: and adjourn on the motion of Vice President Lazaro to report this paper to the regular meeting and adjourn, seconded by Councilor Callahan.

538
00:53:08,034 --> 00:53:08,694
[SPEAKER_15]: All those in favor?

539
00:53:09,395 --> 00:53:09,935
[SPEAKER_15]: Opposed?

540
00:53:10,095 --> 00:53:11,936
[SPEAKER_15]: The motion passes and the meeting is adjourned.

541
00:53:12,496 --> 00:53:13,837
[SPEAKER_15]: We're using the same Zoom link for 7 p.m.

542
00:53:13,857 --> 00:53:17,559
[SPEAKER_15]: So if you're on Zoom and you want to stick around for the regular meeting, stay on Zoom.

543
00:53:18,619 --> 00:53:23,602
[SPEAKER_15]: And if not, come down and join us in the chamber or watch on YouTube or Medford Community Media.

544
00:53:23,922 --> 00:53:25,743
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you and we'll see you back here at 7.

